[1]
Date: Tue 20 Oct 2009
Source: thesentinel.co.uk [edited]
<http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/tvradio/TV-Preview-Nature-Shock-Cannibal-Hippos-8211-8pm/article-1432767-detail/article.html>


Nature shock: cannibal hippos
-----------------------------
In 2004, the Queen Elizabeth National Park [QENP] in Uganda was
confronted with a most disturbing mystery. Not only had some fool
commissioned another series of Wild At Heart, but, after a long spell
of dry weather, hippopotamuses began dying in large numbers along the
shores of the Kazinga Channel. Carcasses were found bobbing in the
water next to live hippos and the initial theory that the deaths were
caused by fighting was ruled out when keepers discovered a number of
peaceable females among the dead. Park wardens theorised that
poaching was to blame, until they saw that the ivory teeth of the
animals had been left intact. Vets then began to wonder if the deaths
were due to an infection. And tests revealed that the culprit was
indeed anthrax.

It became a race against time to identify the source of the outbreak
before more animals became infected. But how was it that hippos all
over the park were dying? The answer came when vets noticed some
unusual behaviour -- hippos chewing on the carcasses' intestines,
which had been expelled from the body by the gases inside. With the
dry weather killing off vegetation, the hippos had been forced to
seek other food sources -- including their own kind. The notion was
initially met with derision -- not least because hippos never eat
meat. But the astonishing theory now seemed irrefutable --
hunger-stricken hippos in Uganda were eating the infected corpses of
their brethren, only to become infected with anthrax themselves.

--
