[3]
Date: Wed 21 Oct 2009
From: Fabian Leendertz <LeendertzF@rki.de> [edited]


Basically the epidemic started at one point, maybe 2, and then
progressed continuously. This is atypical for normal point-source
anthrax outbreaks, which would have resulted in a more patchy
distribution and probably fewer dead animals.

The explanation of cannibalism came through my observation that they
were eating the expelled intestines of dead animals. In this way one
index case when eaten would result in the group being infected, and so onwards.

Analyses of water were negative, possibly due to the dilution effects
of water currents and animal activity.

My observation of cannibalism needs to be confirmed by others.

--
Fabian Leendertz
Robert Koch-Institut
Germany
<LeendertzF@rki.de>

******
[4]
Date: Tue 20 Oct 2009
From: Joseph Dudley <fnjpd@uaf.edu>


In a 2004 letter to ProMED-mail (archive number 20041214.3308), I
speculated that the large numbers of anthrax fatalities among hippos
during the 2004 anthrax outbreak in QENP, when contrasted with
notable lack of contemporaneous observations of observed anthrax
cases among buffalo and other normally susceptible ungulate species,
suggested that cannibalism of anthrax-infected hippo carcasses might
be driving this outbreak. [See ProMED-mail archive no. 20041215.3317
for confirmation by John Woodford.]

On a trip to the site of this outbreak earlier this year (June 2009),
my observations of the extremely high frequency and intimacy of
contacts between buffalo and hippos in water and on land within the
riparian areas of the Kazinga Channel where the outbreak occurred
appeared to support my hypothesis that some phenomenon must have been
involved in the 2004-2005 outbreak other than simple environmental
exposures of hippos and buffalo to contaminated forage, soil, or water.

Interestingly, high frequencies of anthrax mortality among hippos,
coupled with low frequencies in other species, were recorded by
Turnbull and colleagues during anthrax outbreaks in the Luangwa
Valley of Zambia in 1987 and 1988. I have seen film footage from the
Luangwa Valley of hippos feeding on buffalo carcasses, and it may be
that hippos there also occasionally feed on hippo carcasses as well,
as has been observed at sites in at least 3 countries that I am aware
of (Uganda, Tanzania, Malawi).

The much higher observed frequencies of anthrax mortality among
hippos in the 1987-1988 anthrax outbreaks suggests that that this
outbreak, like the QENP outbreak of 2004-2005, may have been
exacerbated by hippos feeding upon the carcasses of hippos and other
animals killed by anthrax.

References
----------
Turnbull PCB, Bell RHV, et al (1991): Anthrax in wildlife in the
Luangwa Valley, Zambia. Veterinary Record 128:399-403 [abstract
available
at
<http://veterinaryrecord.bvapublications.com/cgi/content/abstract/128/17/399>].

--
Joseph P Dudley, PhD
<fnjpd@uaf.edu>

[My final comment is to be very careful when near hippopotami. - Mod.MHJ]

